Table \ref{coef} gives the estimated coefficients for our model. We estimate the expected power bill to be \$104.89 during non-summer months for regular power and \$180.31 during summer months (June - September). For solar power the peak season months are November through February with an estimated expected bill of \$83.87 and \$21.50 for non peak season months. Even during the winter months when solar panels do not generate as much electricity, the expected power bill is lower for solar during the winter months than regular power during the winter months. While these estimates indicate that solar power saves money, we are interested in predicting how much money has alreacy been saved from switching to solar and predicting our future savings in order to estimate how many years it will take for solar to pay for itself.
