Figure \ref{future:pred} shows the estimated savings for each month into the future from switching to solar and corresponding 95\% prediction intervals. The cyclical pattern of the estimated savings is due to the choice of our model, with different seasonal effects for solar and non solar. Customers save less during winter months when the difference between solar and regular power bills is less and save much more in summer months when regular power bills rise and solar power bills drop. To date the consumer has saved an estimated \$2000, with a 95\% prediction interval of (\$1763.75,\$2236.94). In just under two years, the costumer has regained a quarter of their initial investment through savings from switching to solar power. 

We are also interested in the number of additional months until the costumer regains their total investment for switching to solar power. The blue lines in figure \ref{future:pred} correspond to the estimated number years and prediction intervals after switching to solar until the constumer regains their \$8000 dollar investment. It is estimated that it will take an additional 70 months (5.8 years) from February 2018 for solar power to pay for itself. This brings the total estimated time for solar to pay for itself to be 7 years and 8 months with a lower bound of the 95\% prediction interval 7 years and 2 months and the upper bound 8 years and 3 months. The width of this interval is only a year wide, which is a a very good interval estimate for the amount of time it takes for solar to pay for itself. 


